Natural Light: The Ultimate Shape-Shifter
Sunlight is the best source of light, but itâ€™s also the most unpredictable. Throughout the day, the way it hits your walls will change:
Morning Light (East-Facing Rooms): If you have an east-facing room, expect a warm, golden glow in the morning that gradually fades as the day progresses. Colors can appear rich and warm early on but may look more muted in the afternoon.
Afternoon Light (West-Facing Rooms): The opposite is true for west-facing roomsâ€”muted mornings, with colors coming to life in the late afternoon as the sun sets and casts a warmer, golden hue.
North-Facing Rooms: These spaces receive cooler, indirect light throughout the day. Because of this, colors tend to look a bit darker and more subdued. If you love warm tones, this is a great place to use them to counteract the coolness.
South-Facing Rooms: If your room is lucky enough to get consistent sunlight all day, most colors will look pretty true-to-swatch. However, bright whites and pastels can feel even brighter, while darker shades can appear a bit softer.
ðŸ’¡ Tip: Always test your paint swatches at different times of the day to see how they shift in natural light!

Artificial Light: Your Roomâ€™s Nighttime Personality
Since we donâ€™t rely on sunlight 24/7, artificial lighting plays a huge role in how colors look once the sun goes down. Hereâ€™s what you need to know:
1. Warm vs. Cool Bulbs
Warm white bulbs (2700K-3000K): These give off a yellowish glow, making warm tones like reds, oranges, and yellows feel cozy, while cooling down blues and grays.
Cool white bulbs (3500K-4100K): A bit more neutral, these bulbs help colors stay truer without too much warmth or coolness.
Daylight bulbs (5000K+): These mimic natural light with a bright, crisp effect that can make bold colors pop but may wash out softer tones.
ðŸ’¡ Tip: If youâ€™re not sure which bulb to go with, try adjustable LED bulbs that let you switch between warm and cool tones!

Different Types of Lighting and Their Effects
Overhead Lighting
Ceiling lights spread illumination across the entire room, but they can sometimes create shadows that darken certain parts of the space. If you have a bold color on your walls, overhead lighting might intensify it.
Lamps & Task Lighting
Table lamps and floor lamps usually give off a softer glow, which can make a room feel cozier. Be mindful of the bulb type because a warm light will enhance earthy tones, while a cool light will amplify cooler shades.
Accent Lighting
Spotlights, wall sconces, and under-cabinet lighting can highlight certain areas, which can create depth and contrast. If you have a textured wall or a feature wall, accent lighting can enhance its appearance significantly.

How to Choose the Right Paint Color for Your Lighting
So now that you know how light can mess with your paint choices, how do you pick the right color? Here are some pro tips:
Test Before You Commit: Always sample your paint colors on different walls and check them at various times of the day.
Consider the Roomâ€™s Main Light Source: If your room gets mostly artificial light, factor in the bulb type before settling on a color.
Use Large Swatches: Donâ€™t rely on tiny paint chips! Paint a sizable section of the wall (or use peel-and-stick samples) to see the true effect.
Think About the Mood You Want: Warmer tones create a cozy, inviting space, while cooler tones give off a fresh, modern vibe.
Balance Your Colors with Light Fixtures: If you love warm lighting, stick to warm-based paint colors, and vice versa for cool lighting.

